<h1 class="topheadline">Useful (free) Software for School</h1>


<p>Below is a list of software tools that I have found useful for school work and projects.</p>

<div class="subheadline">Mathematical</div>

<ul>
	<li><a href="" class="outlink">LattE</a>: Great tool for finding lattice points in polytopes and integrating polynomials over polytopes. Disclaimer: I have worked on this project.</li>
	<li><a href="" class="outlink">Polymake</a>: Great tool for finding everything you want to know about polytopes. Disclaimer: I am friendly with the people on this project.</li>
	<li><a href="" class="outlink">Sage</a>: I have never used it personally, but I am impressed with what it can do. It seems to work like a free version Maple.</li>
	<li><a href="http://www.wolframalpha.com/" class="outlink">Wolfram Alpha</a>: great online math tool.</li>
</ul>

<div class="subheadline">Other tools</div>

IDE's

<ul>
	<li><span class="b">Java</span>: I have used Eclipse and Netbeans. Both are good, but I like Eclipse better because I feel it is more powerful in terms of addons and the size of the community. I have also used Eclipse for Google's Android API, C++, and PHP. I do not like the Eclipse addon for Latex.</li>
	<li><span class="b">Latex</span>: I started off using <a href="http://www.texniccenter.org/" class="outlink">TexnicCenter</a> but I felt limited, but I think they now have a new version. I have TexWorks that comes with MiKTeX 2.9 but I am not impressed. I tried <a href="http://www.lyx.org/" class="outlink">LyX</a> but I felt I didn't have enough control. I'm currently using <a href="http://www.xm1math.net/texmaker/" class="outlink">TexMaker</a> and I'm more-or-less happy. In the perfect world, OpenOffice would have a formula editor that could understand Latex.</li>
</ul>


